        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The mean is a coordinate in N-dimensional space, which represents the\nlocation where samples are most likely to be generated.  This is\nanalogous to the peak of the bell curve for the one-dimensional or\nunivariate normal distribution."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Covariance indicates the level to which two variables vary together.\nFrom the multivariate normal distribution, we draw N-dimensional\nsamples, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "X = [x_1, x_2, ... x_N]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".  The covariance matrix\nelement "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "C_{ij}"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the covariance of "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "x_i"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " and "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "x_j"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".\nThe element "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "C_{ii}"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the variance of "
              },
              {
                "kind": "math",
                "latex": "x_i"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " (i.e. its\n\"spread\")."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Instead of specifying the full covariance matrix, popular\napproximations include:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "items": [
              {
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "inline": [
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "Spherical covariance ("
                      },
                      {
                        "external_url": "",
                        "href": "/docs/api/ops/cov",
                        "kind": "link",
                        "target": "cov",
                        "text": "cov"
                      },
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": " is a multiple of the identity matrix)"
                      }
                    ],
                    "type": "paragraph"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "inline": [
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "Diagonal covariance ("
                      },
                      {
                        "external_url": "",
                        "href": "/docs/api/ops/cov",
                        "kind": "link",
                        "target": "cov",
                        "text": "cov"
                      },
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": " has non-negative elements, and only on\nthe diagonal)"
                      }
                    ],
                    "type": "paragraph"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ],
            "ordered": false,
            "type": "list"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "This geometrical property can be seen in two dimensions by plotting\ngenerated data-points:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "mean = [0, 0]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "cov = [[1, 0], [0, 100]]  # diagonal covariance"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Diagonal covariance means that the variables are independent, and the\nprobability density contours have their axes aligned with the coordinate axes:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "x, y = fnp.random.multivariate_normal(mean, cov, 5000).T"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.plot(x, y, 'x')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.axis('equal')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.show()"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Note that the covariance matrix must be positive semidefinite (a.k.a.\nnonnegative-definite). Otherwise, the behavior of this method is\nundefined and backwards compatibility is not guaranteed."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "raw_kind": "footnote",
            "raw_text": "1\n\nPapoulis, A., \"Probability, Random Variables, and Stochastic\nProcesses,\" 3rd ed., New York: McGraw-Hill, 1991.",
            "type": "raw_block"
          },
          {
            "raw_kind": "footnote",
            "raw_text": "2\n\nDuda, R. O., Hart, P. E., and Stork, D. G., \"Pattern\nClassification,\" 2nd ed., New York: Wiley, 2001.",
            "type": "raw_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "References"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "mean = (1, 2)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "cov = [[1, 0], [0, 1]]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "x = fnp.random.multivariate_normal(mean, cov, (3, 3))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "x.shape"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "(3, 3, 2)"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Here we generate 800 samples from the bivariate normal distribution\nwith mean [0, 0] and covariance matrix [[6, -3], [-3, 3.5]].  The\nexpected variances of the first and second components of the sample\nare 6 and 3.5, respectively, and the expected correlation\ncoefficient is -3/sqrt(6*3.5) \u2248 -0.65465."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "cov = fnp.array([[6, -3], [-3, 3.5]])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "pts = fnp.random.multivariate_normal([0, 0], cov, size=800)"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Check that the mean, covariance, and correlation coefficient of the\nsample are close to the expected values:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "pts.mean(axis=0)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([ 0.0326911 , -0.01280782])  # may vary"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "fnp.cov(pts.T)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([[ 5.96202397, -2.85602287],"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       [-2.85602287,  3.47613949]])  # may vary"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "fnp.corrcoef(pts.T)[0, 1]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "-0.6273591314603949  # may vary"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "We can visualize this data with a scatter plot.  The orientation\nof the point cloud illustrates the negative correlation of the\ncomponents of this sample."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.plot(pts[:, 0], pts[:, 1], '.', alpha=0.5)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.axis('equal')"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.grid()"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.show()"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Examples"
      }
